MACINTOSH IIci

•	What year was it made? 1989-1993
•	What operating system does it run? Mac OS 7.6.1 
•	How much did it cost (then and now, adjusted for inflation)? How hard is it to find one on the secondhand market (check eBay and Craig’s List). In 1989, the Macintosh IIci sold for $6,000-$8,000 ($12,000 adjusted for inflation).  eBay has several Macintosh IIci computers for sale today, with some listed at prices as low as $75.
•	In brief (a short paragraph), what were its historical strengths and weaknesses as a platform? What was it best known for?
The Macintosh IIci was a very popular platform for Macintosh. It was produced for nearly four years, had significant processing speed, the capability of producing color graphics, and had the ability to store a great deal of memory (more memory could be add to the platform, too). The computer was known for its utility in the business world.  One of the primary weaknesses of the Macintosh was the cost of the computer. The cost was due to the memory and processing speed available in the platform, which was more than most home users would have required. Using the Macintosh IIci, I opened several programs. Between WordPerfect and MS Word, I was unable to discern any major differences, though MS Word had a more familiar layout. The platform contained many programs to include, Publisher, Page Maker, Anti-Virus (which I found very interesting after reading about the SCA Virus on the Amiga), Scrapbook and Puzzle. Interestingly, each file contained information to include; date created, date modified and provided a section for entering comments on a file. Past users were able to save a profile to the computer allowing them to comment on files created in the computer and display their activity.
